'''Elsie Goldsack Pittman''' (''née'' Goldsack; 21 January 1904 – 28 March 1975) was an English tennis player who competed during the second half of the 1920s and the 1930s.

Between 1925 and 1939 she participated in 15 [[Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon players archive – Elsie Pittman (Goldsack)|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/players/7c5b3519-47c0-4c66-b249-9a3a24386b57/index.html|publisher=AELTC}}</ref> Her best result in the singles event was reaching the semifinal in [[1929 Wimbledon Championships|1929]] in which she was defeated in straight sets by first-seeded and eventual champion [[Helen Wills]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon draws archive – 1929 Ladies' Singles – Singles|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/1929/LS/rSs1.html|publisher=AELTC}}</ref> In the mixed doubles she reached the quarterfinal in 1930 and 1931. Her biggest success at [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] level came in 1937 when she partnered with [[Phyllis Mudford King]] to reach the final of the [[1937 Wimbledon Championships]], which they lost to [[Simonne Mathieu]] and [[Billie Yorke]] in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon draws archive – 1937 Ladies' Doubles|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/1937/LD/rFs1.html|publisher=AELTC}}</ref><ref name=robertson>{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|title=The Encyclopedia of Tennis|year=1974|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|isbn=9780047960420|page=361}}</ref>

In 1932 she reached the semifinal of the singles event at the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] and as earlier at Wimbledon she lost in straight sets to the first-seeded and eventual champion, in this case [[Helen Jacobs]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Bud|title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis|year=2010|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=[New York]|isbn=978-0942257700|page=469|edition=2nd}}</ref> During the same tournament she reached the semifinal of the mixed doubles event. That year she also won the singles title at the Eastern Grass Court Championships in [[Rye (city), New York|Rye, N.Y.]] after defeating [[Joan Ridley]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sutter and Mangin in Rye Net Finals|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=u65QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1CEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5924%2C6585356|work=The Milwaukee Journal|agency=AP|date=14 August 1932|page=4}}</ref>

In September 1931 she won the singles title at the invitational tournament at the Ardsley Club.<ref>{{cite news|title=English Women Wins Ardsley Club Tennis|url=http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2017/Dobbs%20Ferry%20NY%20%20Register/Dobbs%20Ferry%20NY%20%20Register%201931/Dobbs%20Ferry%20NY%20%20Register%201931%20-%200615.pdf|newspaper=Dobbs Ferry Register|date=25 September 1931}}</ref> In 1931 and 1932 she won the Middle States Women's Tennis Championships, in both cases after defeating compatriot Joan Ridley in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16904674 |title=TENNIS IN U.S.A. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=12 September 1932  |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

On 4 January 1930 she married J.B. Pittman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tennis Star Weds|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19300117-1.2.111.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=17 January 1930|page=19}}</ref>

